1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 (5... Be7 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 Bg4 { [%csl Gd1][%cal Gg4d1] }) 6. e3 { [%csl Ge7][%cal Gc8f5,Gf8e7] } (6. Qc2 { Is very likely to transpose to the mainline } 6... Bd6 7. e3 (7. Bxf6 Qxf6 { This line is nothing to worry about } 8. Nxd5 Qxd4 9. Rd1 Qh4 { Preventing Nf6+ and maintaining the bishop pair } 10. Nf3 Qh6 11. Nc3 O-O { [%cal Gb8d7,Gd7f6,Gd6c7] }) 7... O-O 8. Bd3 h6 9. Bh4 Re8 { transposes to mainline }) 6... Bd6!? { A lesser common, but recently trendy line which offers black active play against the Queen's Gambit Exchange Variation. IM Kassa Korley popularized this line with a stunning miniature over a strong GM } { [%csl Ge4,Ge5,Gd8][%cal Ge3e4,Ge4e5,Gg5d8] } 7. Bd3 (7. Qc2 { What is white threatening? Be careful to play the right move here! } 7... O-O (7... h6? 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Nxd5) 8. Bd3 h6 9. Bh4 { transposes }) 7... h6 8. Bh4 (8. Bxf6?! { is completely harmless. Black is happy to get the bishop pair and have very solid development } 8... Qxf6 9. Nf3 O-O 10. O-O Bg4) 8... O-O 9. Qc2 (9. Nge2 { Is likely to transpose to mainline. Also keep in mind that the Bxh2 trap still exists! } 9... Re8 10. O-O? Bxh2+ 11. Kxh2 Ng4+ 12. Kg3 g5 $19) 9... Re8 { The most flexible move. Black delays queenside development and will decide how to proceed based on whitte's next move. } 10. Nge2 (10. Nf3 Be6 { A different approach than usual-- Black simply aims to complete development with Nbd7 and prevent white from playing an early Ne5 } 11. O-O (11. Ne5?! { is premature for white. How can black accurately punish this? } 11... c5! { preparing Nc6 and black will have a comfortable setup } { [%cal Gb8c6] } 12. O-O Nc6 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Bxf6 (14. dxc5? Bxh2+ 15. Kh1 (15. Kxh2 Ng4+ 16. Kg3 g5 $19) 15... Bc7 $15) 14... Qxf6 15. dxc5 Bxc5 16. Ne2 Bb6 17. Qxc6 Qxb2) (11. Qb3!? { a rare move played by Grischuk with good success against Xiong } 11... b6 12. O-O Nbd7 13. Rac1 a6 14. Qc2 Qc7 15. Rfe1 c5 16. dxc5 bxc5) 11... Nbd7 { There are many ways the game can branch from here and more analysis is required. Here is one example line: } 12. Rab1 (12. a3 a5 13. Rab1 Rc8!? { prophylaxis against b4 } (13... Qb8 14. Rfc1 { See Aronian-Ding } (14. Bg3 b5 15. Ne2 Bxg3 16. hxg3 Qd6 17. Rfc1 Rec8 18. Nf4 Bg4 19. Nh2)) 14. b4?! (14. Bg3 Bxg3 15. hxg3 b5 16. b4 a4 17. Rfe1 Nb6 18. Ne5 Nc4 19. Bxc4 dxc4 { [%cal Gf6d5] }) 14... b5! 15. Ne2 { Now we see the purpose of the rook on c8 defending the backward c6-pawn. Black can now very quickly maneuver the knight to c4 with a great grip on the queenside } 15... Nb6 $15 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gb6c4] }) 12... a5 (12... Qc7) 13. a3 Qb8 14. b4 b5!?) (10. O-O-O? { Is played far less often and not a move to be so worried about. Here, black's attack will be quite fast on the queenside. } 10... b5 $40 11. Kb1 Na6! { black is now guaranteed to achieve Nb4 or meet a3 with b4. In both scenarios, black will have a decisive advantage }) 10... a5 { Preparing Na6, and slowing down a potential minority attack which could happen later in the middlegame } 11. h3 (11. O-O? { [%csl Gd6,Ge7] } 11... Bxh2+ 12. Kxh2 Ng4+ 13. Kg3 g5 { [%csl Gg3] } 14. Bf5 gxh4+ 15. Kh3 h5 16. g3 Re4! 17. Bxc8 Qxc8 18. Kg2 Qf5 19. Nxe4 h3+ 20. Kg1 Qf3 $19) (11. Bg3 Bxg3 12. Nxg3 (12. hxg3 Ng4) 12... Na6 13. a3 h5!? 14. h3 (14. O-O h4 15. Nge2 h3 16. g3 Nc7 17. Bf5 Ne4 18. Bxc8 Qxc8 19. Nf4 Qd7) 14... h4 15. Nge2 Nc7 16. O-O g6 17. b4 Nh5 18. b5 cxb5 19. Nxb5 Nxb5 20. Bxb5 Bf5 21. Bd3 Rc8 22. Qd2 Bxd3 23. Qxd3 Qd7 24. Rab1 Rc4 25. Rb6 Re6 26. Rfb1 Rxb6 27. Rxb6 a4 28. Qb1 Rc7 29. Qb4 Kg7) 11... Na6 { [%csl Gb4,Gc2,Gd3][%cal Ga6b4] } 12. a3 { [%csl Ga6] } 12... Nc7 13. O-O Ne6 14. f3 (14. f4 Be7 15. f5 (15. Rae1 b6 { [%cal Gc6c5] }) 15... Ng5) (14. Rad1 Bd7 15. f3 Ng5 16. e4 Nfxe4 17. fxe4 Nxh3+ 18. gxh3 Qxh4 19. Rf2 Bxh3 20. e5 Rxe5 21. dxe5 Bc5 22. Nd4 Bxd4 23. Bh7+ Kh8 24. Rxd4 Qxd4 25. Qd3 Qg4+? { allowed white to equalize ½-½ (48) Ringoir,T (2510)-Korley, K (2437) Charlotte 2019 } (25... Qxe5! 26. Qxh3 Kxh7 27. Rxf7 Re8 $17)) (14. Bg3 Bxg3 15. Nxg3 Bd7 (15... h5!? $146 { There are many ways for the current position to branch out, but here's one example of how white can go very wrong by playing natural moves } 16. b4 (16. f4 c5) 16... h4 17. Nf5? { This natural and energetic move is actually a big mistake! Somehow white's knight will end up stranded on the kingside } (17. Nge2 Nh5 18. b5 Ng5 19. bxc6 bxc6 20. Na4 Qf6 $40) 17... Ng5 18. Nxh4 Nfe4 $19)) 14... Ng5 15. e4? { While this move is quite thematic, it walks straight into a brilliant attacking sequence } (15. f4! { The best move } 15... Ne6 { White is slightly better, but this is still playable } { [%cal Gd6e7,Gb7b6,Gc6c5,Gc8b7,Ge6f8] } 16. Kh1 Be7 17. Ng1 c5!) (15. Bxg5?! hxg5 16. e4 dxe4 17. fxe4 c5! { A strong central counterpunch! White's pawn center will not last } 18. e5 cxd4 19. exd6 dxc3 20. Nxc3 Qxd6 $15 { Black is up a clean pawn abnd white has minimal compensation }) 15... Nfxe4 (15... Ngxe4 16. fxe4) 16. fxe4 Nxh3+ 17. gxh3 Qxh4 { [%csl Gg1] } 18. Rf2 (18. e5 Rxe5! 19. dxe5 { [%csl Gg1][%cal Gc5g1,Gd6c5] } (19. Bf5 Qg5+ 20. Kh1 Bxf5 21. Qc1 Re3 { 0-1 (26) Kashlinskaya,A (2494) -Rosen,E (2353) Chess.com INT 2020 }) 19... Bc5+ 20. Nd4 (20. Kg2 Qxh3#) 20... Bxd4+ 21. Kh1 Qxh3+ 22. Qh2 Qxd3 23. Rad1 Qh3 $19) 18... Bxh3 19. Rd1 Re5!! 20. dxe5 Bc5 21. Nd4 Bxd4 22. Rd2 Qg3+ 23. Kh1 Bg4 { [%csl Gf3][%cal Gg4f3] } 24. Bf1 Bf3+ 25. Bg2 Qh3+ { 0-1 (25) Moiseenko,A (2628) -Korley, K (2437) Helsingor 2019 } 26. Kg1 Qxg2# { [%csl Gg1][%cal Gd4g1] } *


