{ [%evp 0,38,25,26,13,-23,2,4,6,-25,-26,-13,2,22,3,15,25,36,30,29,34,34,0,33,-1,17,17,30,30,30,32,33,27,17,17,26,20,0,0,7,32] }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 { [%csl Gg1,Gc8][%cal Gf1g2,Ge1g1] } 4... dxc4 5. Bg2 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 c5 7. Bxb4 (7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. O-O O-O 9. Qc2 Nbd7 10. Qxc4 b6 (10... b5 11. Qxb5 Rb8 12. Qc4 Rxb2 { [%csl Gb6,Gf2,Ge2,Gf1,Gg1][%cal Gd8b6,Gc8a6,Ga6e2,Gb6f2] })) 7... cxb4 8. Ne5 (8. Qa4+ { A lot of unprepared players will play this move as it is a thematic Catalan idea. However, black is happy to enter the following line with a potential landmine for white to fall into... } 8... Nc6 9. Ne5 Bd7 (9... O-O 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Qxb4 Ba6) 10. Nxc6 Bxc6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Qxc6+ (12. Qxb4 Qxd4) 12... Nd7 13. O-O (13. Qxc4? Rc8! $19 { [%csl Gc4,Gc1,Ge1,Gh1][%cal Gc8c1,Gc1h1] }) 13... Rc8 14. Qa4 a5 15. a3 O-O 16. axb4 Nb6 17. Qb5 axb4 18. Qxb4 Qxd4) (8. a3 { While a3 can be a thematic and challenging idea in this opening, it not the most testing at this specific moment } 8... b5 9. axb4 (9. Ne5 Nd5) 9... Bb7) 8... O-O 9. Nxc4 (9. a3!? { The engine's top choice and a trendy line among many GMs } 9... Nd5 10. Nxc4 Nc6 11. O-O a5 { A useful move to create an eventual outpost on b4 } 12. axb4 (12. Qd2 b5 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 bxa3 15. Nxa3 Qb6) 12... Ndxb4 13. e3 b6 14. Nbd2 Ba6 { Once black finds life for the light-squared bishop, there are no more serious issues. From here, the position is roughly equal. The following game between Erigaisi and Praggnanandhaa shows how white can get outplayed... } 15. Qh5 Rc8 16. b3 b5 17. Ne5 Nxe5 18. Qxe5 h6 19. Ne4 Bb7 20. Rfd1 Bd5 21. Nc5 Bxg2 22. Kxg2 Qb6 23. Qe4 Rc7 24. Rdc1 Rd8 25. h4 Nd5 26. Qf3 e5 27. Rd1 exd4 28. exd4 Re7 29. Re1 Rxe1 30. Rxe1 Nf6 31. Rd1 Nd5 32. h5 Qa7 33. Ne4 a4 34. bxa4 bxa4 35. Nc5 Nb6 36. Qd3 a3 37. Ra1 Ra8 38. Qb3 a2 39. Ne4 Qb7 40. f3 Qa6 41. Kh3 Qc8+ 42. g4 Qa6 (42... Qe6! $19) 43. d5 Nc4 44. Nc3 Nd2 45. Qxa2 Qxa2 46. Rxa2 Rxa2 47. Nxa2 Nxf3 48. Kg3 Ng5 49. Nc3 Kf8 50. Kf4 Ke7 51. Nb5 g6 52. Ke5 Nf3+ 53. Kf4 Ng5 54. Ke5 Nf3+ 55. Kf4 Ng5 { 1/2-1/2 (55) Erigaisi,A (2725) -Praggnanandhaa,R (2676) chess24.com INT 2022 }) 9... Nc6 10. e3 e5! { A strong temporary pawn sacrifice. If not for this move, black would have a difficult time finding activity } 11. d5 (11. Nxe5?! Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qxd1+ 13. Kxd1 Ng4 14. Ke2 Nxe5 15. Rc1 Bg4+! { It is useful for black to provoke f3 which blunts the power of the g2-bishop } 16. f3 Bd7 $17 { [%cal Gd7b5] }) (11. Bxc6?! { Giving away the light-squared bishop is a huge concession. With black keeping the light-squared bishop and many light-squared wholes in white's kingside pawn structure, black is guaranteed sufficient compensation for the pawn. } 11... bxc6 12. Nxe5 c5 $44) (11. dxe5 Qxd1+ 12. Kxd1 Ng4 { [%csl Gf2,Ge5,Ge6,Gd8][%cal Gc8e6,Gf8d8,Gd8d1] } 13. Ke2 Ngxe5 14. Nbd2 Bg4+ 15. f3 Bf5 16. e4 Bd7 { See Mikhalevski-Robson for an absolute brilliancy! }) 11... b5 (11... Ne7) (11... Bg4 12. f3 { [%csl Gg4,Gc6] }) 12. dxc6 Qxd1+ 13. Kxd1 bxc4 14. a3 (14. c7 Bg4+ 15. Kc1 (15. f3 Be6) 15... Rac8) 14... Bg4+ (14... b3 15. Nc3) 15. Kc1 (15. f3 Be6 16. axb4 Nd5 { [%cal Gd5e3,Gd5b4] } 17. b5 Rab8 (17... Nxe3+?! 18. Ke2 Nxg2 19. Nc3! $16 { somehow the engine gives white a clear edge here. For this reason, I suggest avoiding 17...Nxe3 }) 18. Nc3 Nxc3+ 19. bxc3 Rxb5) 15... b3 { See Rasmussen-Robson 2009 for a mindblowing finish } (15... a5 16. Nd2 (16. h3 Be2! { a nice way to defend the c4 pawn (in case white attacks it with knight d2. Black now has the idea of combining e4 and Bd3 to dominate the position } { [%csl Gc4,Gd3,Ge4][%cal Ge5e4,Ge2d3] }) 16... Be6 17. Rd1 b3 18. Nb1 Ng4 19. Rd2 f5 $15 { [%csl Rc6][%cal Ge5e4] }) 16. Nc3 Rac8 17. h3 Be6 18. Rd1 Rfd8 19. f4 e4 20. g4 Nd5 21. Bxe4 Nxe3 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. c7 Rd4 24. Bb7 h6 25. f5 Bd7 26. c8=Q+ Bxc8 27. Bxc8 Kf8 28. Ba6 Rd6 29. Bb7 a5 30. Bf3 Ke7 31. a4 Rd4 32. Be2 Kf6 33. h4 Ke5 34. Rb1 Kf4 35. Nb5 Rd7 36. Nc3 Kg3 37. g5 hxg5 38. hxg5 Kf2 39. Bh5 Ke1 40. f6 gxf6 41. gxf6 Rd2 42. Ra1 Rc2+ 43. Kb1 Nf1 { 0-1 (43) Rasmussen,A (2536)-Robson,R (2491) Tromsoe 2009 } *


