{ [%evp 0,28,25,26,13,-23,2,-29,-6,6,41,3,0,20,9,-25,-38,-51,-63,-80,-80,-71,-79,-75,-75,-77,-91,-86,-100,-103,-94] Here, we will see how to punish players who try to react "naturally" to the Cambridge Springs, but walk into immediate trouble. Combined, the dubious moves shown in this file have been played hundreds of thousands of times online. So if you play the Cambridge Springs consistently enough, you're likely to encounter them once in a while! Hopefully this will act as a useful guide for how to punish many of white's potential mistakes! Note: it's more important to absorb the tactical themes in this file rather than purely memorize the specific variations. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 { [%csl Gf6,Ge6] } 4. Nf3 (4. Bg5 Nbd7 5. e3 c6 6. Bd3 { This is a less common move order for white since the white knight is not yet developed to f3. It is worth noting this move order since a nice trap exists... } 6... Qa5 { A Cambridge Springs setup still makes the most since despite the slight difference in white's development. All the typical Cambridge Springs plans of exploiting the g5-bishop and c3-knight still exist. Here, white is likely to transpose into one of the dubious lines with Nf3, or blunder material with Ne2? } 7. Ne2? { As of May 2023, over 3, 000 games have reached this position on lichess. Black to move and win material! } (7. Nf3 { transposes to the mainline with 7.Bd3?! }) (7. Bxf6 Nxf6 { Black is happy to snag the bishop pair. Ideas of Bb4 and c5 will likely follow. }) 7... dxc4! { [%cal Ga5g5,Gc4d3] } 8. Bxf6 cxd3 { Since the e2-knight is attacked, there is no way for white to save material. Black has a decisive advantage. } 9. Qxd3 Nxf6 $19) 4... Nbd7 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Qa5 { The beginning of the Cambridge Springs } { [%csl Ra5][%cal Gd8a5] } 7. Bd3?! { This natural developing move in one of the most common mistakes a lot of inexperienced players will make. } (7. c5?! { While this move may look irritating at first as it grabs space and blocks black's dark squared bishop, it is a classic mistake. Black can still grab initiative with an immediate Ne4 and is also very quick to play b6, which will remove white's c-pawn and allow the dark-squared bishop to activate. } 7... Ne4 8. Qc2 b6 9. cxb6 Bb4 10. Rc1 (10. b7 { doesn't help white much } 10... Bxb7 11. Rc1 c5) 10... axb6 { There is now no way for white to defend the a-pawn } 11. Bd3 { It's time to simplify... } 11... Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Nxg5 13. Nxg5 h6 14. Nf3 Qxa2 $17 { With an extra pawn and control of the open a-file black has a very healthy advantage }) (7. Qc2?! Ne4 { Nearly 60% of lichess games will feature white responding with Bf4 or Bh4 which allows black to pile on the pressure... } 8. Bf4 { The most played move on lichess } (8. Bd3?? { Nearly 9,000 games on lichess have reached this position } 8... Nxg5 9. Nxg5 dxc4 $19 { Wins a piece } { [%csl Rd3,Rg5][%cal Gc4d3,Ga5g5] }) (8. cxd5 { Objectively the best move according to the engine, but this is only played 8.5% of the time on lichess } 8... exd5 9. Bd3 Nxg5 10. Nxg5 g6 { Diffusing the power of white's queen/ bishop battery and no longer has to worry about the h7 falling. Black plans to complete development with Bg7, Nf6, and 0-0 } { [%cal Gf8g7,Gd7f6] }) (8. Bh4 Bb4 $40 { is very similar to 8.Bf4 }) 8... Bb4 9. Rc1 { Defending c3, but leaving a2 undefended! } (9. a3!? { objectively the best move, but very rarely played. } 9... Nxc3 10. Qb3! { Somehow white manages to be okay here. Realistically, you don't have to worry about this variation happening, but here's a simle line if it somehow does... } 10... Ne2+ 11. Qxb4 (11. Kxe2 Be7 { [%csl Re2] }) 11... Qxb4+ 12. axb4 Nxf4 13. exf4 dxc4 14. Bxc4 Nf6 { Despite having a still passive light-squared bishop, black is for choice with much better pawn structure. } { [%csl Rb4,Rd4][%cal Ge8e7,Gh8d8] }) 9... Qxa2 10. Bd3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Qxc2 12. Rxc2 Be7 $17 { black is up a clean pawn }) (7. a3?! { While this move prevents bishop Bb4, is loses time and still allows black to seize intiative } 7... Ne4 8. Rc1 (8. Qc2? { The most played move on lichess (played in 13,000+ games). This loses a pawn. } 8... Nxg5 9. Nxg5 dxc4 { White has no time to recapture on c4 since the g5-knight is hanging } { [%cal Ga5g5] } 10. Nf3 b5 $17 { Black is up a clean pawn and white has no compensation } { [%cal Gf8e7,Gc8b7,Ge8g8,Gc6c5] }) (8. b4? { An interesting try and the second most played move on lichess (~5000 games), but this fails tactically. } 8... Bxb4! 9. axb4 Qxb4 10. Rc1 Nxc3 11. Qd2 Na2! { Solving all of black's problems! This forces the queen, and the knight will survive to tell its grandchildren all about it's heroic opening feats. } 12. Ra1 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 Nb4 $17 { Black is up two extra pawns and white has minimal compensation }) 8... dxc4 9. Bf4 Nxc3 10. Rxc3 Bxa3! $19) (7. Rc1?! Ne4 8. Bf4 { most commonly played } { [%csl Gf4] } (8. cxd5 Nxg5 { Black is happy to snag the bishop pair and displace white's kingside knight } 9. Nxg5 exd5 { recapturing with the e-pawn is the most logical to make way for the eventual development of the light-squared bishop } 10. Bd3 Nf6 11. O-O Bd6 12. e4 { This is the most-played move in the lichess database and looks quite logical as white aims to open the center before black can castle. However, this is a serious blunder. Black to move and win material! } (12. f4 { A better approach than blundering } 12... h6 13. Nf3 Bg4 { With this move, black pins the knight and prevent Ne5. In any case where white breaks the pin with Qe1 or Qc2, black is happy to capture on f3. The position is now very stable for black and probably slightly preferable. In many cases the plan is to castle queenside and begin pressuring the backward e3-pawn with Re8 } { [%csl Re3][%cal Ge8c8,Gh8e8,Ge8e3] } 14. Qe1) 12... Bf4! { [%csl Rc1,Rg5][%cal Gf4g5,Gf4c1] } 13. e5 Bxg5 14. exf6 Bxf6 $17 { In this case it's much better to take the pawn and avoid greediness with Bxc1. Black now much better with the extra pawn and bishop pair. }) 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 (9. Rxc3? Bb4 $19) 9... Ba3! { A lessy greedy approach. Instead of grabbing the a2-pawn, black seizes initiative and aims to rapidly complete development while maintaining control on the queenside. } 10. Rc2 b6 { A typical move, preparing Ba6 and giving life to the "depressed" light-squared bishop } { [%csl Ga6][%cal Gc8a6] } 11. cxd5?! { This is the most played move on lichess, but a clear inaccuracy. Black is happy to open the c-file and soon target the backwards c-pawn } (11. Bd3 { A better approach than 11.cxd5 } 11... Ba6 12. Nd2 O-O { Roughly equal, but more pleasant for black. Plans include c5 and Rc8 targeting white's vulnerable queenside pawn }) 11... cxd5 12. Bd3 Ba6 13. O-O Rc8 $15 { Black is ready to castle next and later build up even more pressure against the c3-pawn by doubling rooks on the c-file. } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Gc8c6,Gh8c8,Gc8c3] }) (7. Qb3?! { Originally, I wasn't going to include this move in the file since it's played so infrequently, but I encountered it online the same day I was annotating this PGN! Here's a fun approach for black... } 7... Ne4 8. Bf4 g5! { This energetic pawn thrust becomes possible when the queen is on b3, since there are line where dxc4 will attack the queen on b3 and a minor piece on g5. } { [%csl Gg5] } 9. Bg3 (9. Nxg5? Nxg5 10. Bxg5 dxc4 $19 { [%csl Gg5,Gb3][%cal Ga5g5,Gc4b3] }) 9... h5 $40 10. h4 Nxg3 11. fxg3 gxh4 12. gxh4 Nf6 $15 { The knight will find a great post on g4 and combine nicely with Bh6 to pressure the weak e3 pawn. } { [%csl Re3,Gg4][%cal Gf6g4,Gf8h6] }) (7. Be2?! Ne4 8. O-O { The best move } (8. Qc2?! { The most played move, but this loses material to a simple sequence } 8... Nxg5 9. Nxg5 dxc4 $15 { Black wins a clean pawn as white has no time to recapture on c4. Black is likely to follow up with b5 reinforcing c4. } { [%cal Ga5g5] }) 8... Nxg5 9. Nxg5 dxc4 10. Nge4 Nb6 11. Nd2 g6 12. Nxc4 Nxc4 13. Bxc4 Bg7 { The dust has settled! Now there are clear plans for completing development and eventually opening the center with a c5 or e5 break so the bishops can flourish. } { [%cal Ge8g8,Gb7b6,Gc6c5,Gc8b7,Ge6e5] }) (7. Qa4? { This silly attempt to trade queens is simply bad } 7... Qxa4 8. Nxa4 dxc4 $19 { Black wins a clean pawn and white can't easily recapture with Bxc4 due to b5! } { [%cal Gb7b5] }) 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 Ne4 { A strong fork! Black now attacks both the g5-bishop and the c3-knight. Both pieces have two attackers and only one defender. } 9. Bf4 { This is the most common move among players rated 1600+ in the lichess database. White saves the bishop and accepts the fact that the queenside is about to crumble. } (9. Qc2?? { hilariously, this is the most commonly played move overall on lichess with nearly 8000 games as of May 2023. This simply loses the bishop for nothing. } 9... Nxg5 10. Nxg5 Qxg5 $19) (9. Bh4 { This is less commonly played the bishop has less purpose on h4. In this case, black can take the more direct approach } 9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 Qxc3+ { [%csl Gc4] } 11. Nd2 Bb4 { Black is now threatening Qxc4 as the d2-knight will be pinned by the bishop } 12. Rc1 (12. O-O? { simply loses the knight } 12... Qxd2) 12... Qxd2+ 13. Qxd2 Bxd2+ 14. Kxd2 e5! { this move would not be possible in this variation if the bishop had gone to f4. } 15. d5 f6 16. dxc6 bxc6 17. Bd3 c5 $15 { While white does have some compensation for the pawn, it is only black who can be better here. c5 combines nicely with the light-squared bishop and black has easy play with ideas of Bb7, Ke7, and eventually bringing the rooks into the game. }) (9. Qa4? { An interesting attempt, but this fails to a simple tactic } 9... Qxa4 10. Nxa4 b5 $19) 9... e5!! { An engine-inspired move which is extremely rare in human play. This approach causes some big issues for white and creates many opportunities for white to further go wrong. This is a temporary pawn sacrifice, but the general idea is to open the center so black's light-squared bishop can later get involved. In many cases, black will continually make threats until winning back material. } (9... Nxc3 { It's totally possible to go for this more straight forward approach, but white does end up getting a bit of compensation for the lost pawn } 10. bxc3 Qxc3+ 11. Nd2 Bb4 12. Rc1 Qxd2+ 13. Qxd2 Bxd2+ 14. Kxd2 O-O { While black should still be for choice, the position is very close to equal. White has good compensation for the pawn with the bishop pair and more activity. For this reason, I recommend going for 9. e5!! }) 10. dxe5 (10. Nxe5? { This immediately loses material since white will not have Nd2 and the end of the variation } 10... Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Qxc3+ $19 { White does not have Nd2 to defend everything. Black is now winning. } { [%cal Gc3e1,Gc3c4] }) (10. Bg3 { The top engine move, but very difficult for a human to play (only played in 5 out of 44 games in the lichess database). Black will still retain a pleasant edge. } 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Qxc3+ 12. Nd2 Be7 { The simplest approach! Black just wants to complete development, castle, and maintain the extra pawn } 13. Rc1 Qa5 $15 { From a5, the queen keeps the e5-pawn defended. With 0-0 coming next, black has a solid position and white doesn't have much compensation for the pawn. }) 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Qxc3+ 12. Nd2 Nxe5 13. Rc1 Nd3+ 14. Bxd3 Qxd3 $19 *


