1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Qa5 7. Nd2 { This multi-purpose move is the most popular choice in the Masters Database. White attempts to diffuse the pressure along the a5-e1 diagonal while enabling future ideas of Nb3 or Nc4. The downside to this move is that is leave the bishop on g5 undefended (which can often be a tactical target) and slows down white's development. Black is still able to apply central future in an energetic fashion... } 7... Bb4 (7... dxc4 8. Bxf6 Nxf6 9. Nxc4 { [%csl Ga5] }) 8. Qc2 { By far the most popular move. White defends the c3-knight } (8. Qb3? { Falling into a common Cambridge Springs tactical motif. Black to move and win material! } 8... dxc4 9. Nxc4 Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 Qxg5 $19) (8. Bxf6 Nxf6 { This line is nothing to worry about. Black will soon castle and aim for the c5-break. }) (8. Rc1 Ne4 { Based on some deep analysis, Ne4 appears to be objectively the best approach for black. The following is an immensely sharp and fascinating line with lots of engine influence. } 9. Ndxe4 dxe4 10. Bh4 Qxa2 11. Qc2 Nb6 12. Be2 Na4 13. O-O Bxc3 14. bxc3 Nxc3 15. Qxc3 Qxe2 16. Qa3 f6 17. f3 c5! 18. Rfe1 Qd3 19. Qxc5 exf3 20. e4 h5 21. d5 Qd2 22. gxf3 Rh6 23. Qf2 Rg6+ { Deviating from Qxf2?! (which was featured in Cheparinov-Sidhant 2021) } 24. Bg3 Qb4 { Engine gives equality, but still lots of fight in a very imbalanced position! }) 8... e5!? { not the most common approach, but this is a fascinating temporary pawn sacrifice that leads a dynamic position } 9. Bxf6 (9. Nb3 Qc7 10. a3 (10. Be2 { Played by Kramnik to defeat Kamsky in 1993 } 10... Ne4! { Deviating from Kramnik-Kamsky, this is a strong central jab that commences black's initiative } 11. Bh4 g5! 12. Bg3 h5! { This position has never been reached before and can branch out in many directions. Here's one example line of central liquidation } 13. O-O Bxc3 14. bxc3 h4 15. Bxe5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Qxe5 17. cxd5 cxd5 18. Bb5+ Kf8 $13 { Engines give 0.00. There is plenty of room for further analysis, but it is beyond the scope of this course. Refer to arrows for some of black's major ideas. }) 10... Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 O-O { Objectively, white is slightly for choice with the bishop pair, but black's position is now quite stable as the center is well reinforced. } 12. Bd3 h6 13. Bh4 c5!? { a fascinating engine-inspired idea. Black applies maximum pressure to the center before white can castle }) (9. Be2?! exd4 { Black is happy to open the position and leave white with an isolated queen's pawn } 10. exd4 (10. Nb3? dxc3! { oh no my queen! } 11. Nxa5 cxb2+ $19) 10... dxc4 11. Bh4 b5 12. O-O O-O 13. Bf3 Bb7 14. a4 Qb6) (9. dxe5?! { This is the most played move, but not the most testing. } { [%csl Ge5] } 9... Ne4 10. Ndxe4 dxe4 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Ga5e5,Gd7e5] } 11. O-O-O O-O! { A simple and patient move. Now that the d7 knight is no longer pinned to d8, black is threatening to capture on e5 } (11... Nxe5?? 12. Rd8+ $18) 12. Nxe4 { The most critical line } (12. a3 { A safe alternative that leads to equality } 12... Bxc3 13. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 14. bxc3 Re8! { Another patient move. If black takes on e5 instead, Bf4 is a bit annoying. Now, if white plays Bf4 to defend the pawn, black can switch up plans... } 15. Bf4 Nb6 16. Rd4 c5! 17. Rd6 (17. Rxe4? f5 $19) 17... Be6 { black is ready to play Bxc4, winning back the pawn with a comfortable position }) 12... Qxa2 13. f4? (13. Bf4 Qa1+ 14. Qb1 Qa5) 13... h6 14. Bh4 Nc5 15. Nxc5 Bxc5 16. Bf2 Bg4 17. Rd2 Rad8 18. Rxd8 Qa1+! { An important in-between move } 19. Qb1 Qxb1+ 20. Kxb1 Rxd8 $19) 9... Nxf6 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gd4e5] } 10. dxe5 Ne4 11. cxd5 { This is the most played move among masters and the engine's top choice. This line is perhaps an attempt to refute the Cambridge Springs, but we're going to see that black has some crazy ideas and mindblowing novelties to generate a huge headache for white } (11. Ndxe4 { This is the most played move online, but not the most critical. Black will equalize easily. } 11... dxe4 12. Be2 (12. a3 Bf5 { The most flexible move, simply defending the e4-pawn. Black doesn't have to move the dark-squared bishop since the a3-pawn is pinned. Black now keeps the option open of whether to casle kingside or queenside }) 12... Qxe5 $15 13. O-O Bf5 14. Rfd1 Bd6 15. g3 h5 $40) (11. Nb3 { This is the top engine move, but you're very unlikely to encounter this as it's not so natural for white to allow Bxc3 giving back the pawn. This move has been played only 3 times out of 300+ games in the lichess database as of May 2023. } 11... Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qxc3+ 13. Qxc3 Nxc3 { It is not easy for white to maintain an edge in this position without very precise engine play. Here's an example of a natural line that leads to a very playable position for black and rough equality... } 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15. Bc4 Be6 16. Nc5 b5 17. Bb3 O-O-O) (11. Ncxe4 dxe4 12. a3 Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 Qxe5) 11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 Bxc3 13. Rc1 Bb4 (13... Bxe5 14. dxc6 O-O 15. Bd3 g6 16. O-O bxc6 17. Nc4 $14 { This line is not as enjoyable for black }) 14. dxc6 bxc6!! $146 { This move looks like a terrible blunder at first, but has a nasty trap in store... } 15. Qxc6+?? { Astonishingly, this move instantly loses for white. Black is more than happy to sacrifice BOTH ROOKS!!! } (15. a3 Qxa3! { White can still not capture on c6! } 16. Bd3 (16. Qxc6+?? { still loses for white } 16... Bd7 17. Qxa8+ Ke7 18. Qxh8 { It is now forced checkmate... } 18... Qxc1+ 19. Ke2 Bg4+ 20. Kd3 Bf5+ 21. Ke2 Qxd2+ 22. Kf3 Qd5+ 23. Kg3 Qxe5+ 24. f4 Qxe3+ 25. Kh4 Qxf4+ 26. g4 Qxg4#) 16... O-O 17. O-O (17. Bxh7+? Kh8 { Amazingly, black now has a decisive advantage as every white move will be punished } 18. Bd3 (18. O-O Bxd2 { Simply wins a piece due to white's queen being overworked }) 18... Rd8 $19 { The pressure against white is simply overwhelming. Brace yourself for a tactical rampage } 19. Ke2 Bxd2 20. Qxd2 Rxd3! 21. Qxd3 Ba6 $19) 17... Bxd2 18. Qxd2 a5 19. Rxc6 Be6 { Objectively, white should be a bit better with the extra pawn, but black has interesting counter chances with the outside passed a-pawn }) (15. Bd3 { One of the best options for white } 15... O-O 16. Bxh7+ { only leads to issues for white } 16... Kh8 17. Bd3 Rd8 $40) 15... Bd7 16. Qxa8+ Ke7 17. Qxh8 Bxd2+ 18. Ke2 (18. Kd1 Bxc1 19. Kxc1 Qc3+ 20. Kd1 Ba4+ 21. Ke2 Qc4+ 22. Kf3 Bd1+ 23. Kg3 Qg4#) 18... Bg4+ 19. f3 Bxc1 20. Kf2 (20. fxg4 Qd2+ 21. Kf3 Qxe3#) 20... Qxe5 21. e4 Bf4! $19 { White is getting mated by force! The dark-squared bishop prevents the king's g3 getaway and now Qd4 is unstoppable. Checkmate is imminent. } 22. fxg4 Qd4+ 23. Ke2 Qd2+ 24. Kf3 Qe3# { 0-1 Black wins by checkmate. } *


